        The first thing I notice is the light. Not the purple I expected—I saw that through the hull breach—but the quality of it, like stepping into perpetual twilight even though it's midday. Sunlight filters through the canopy overhead, turning everything lavender and soft, dreamlike. Everything glows.

        The second thing is the ground—my boots sink slightly into groundcover that feels like moss but isn't: purple-black and springy, almost pleasant underfoot. I take another step and another, equipment bag heavy on my shoulder. The forest stretches ahead, tree trunks the width of ancient oaks but smooth and burgundy-dark. Looking up, the leaves are nearly black from below, yet when the light catches them just right they glow deep violet.

        Holy shit—I'm on an alien planet.

        In Season three, Episode seven, Mav called this the "first glimpse moment"—stepping onto a new world and taking in everything before the adventure really starts. I get it now—I completely get it.

        Buddy's voice bursts into my head —
        "*Kira, LOOK at this!* Why is everything purple? Is it because the sun is different? The light feels different!"

        I whisper —
        "_It's so beautiful. Buddy, this is actually happening._"

        Buddy replies —
        "*I know!* I've never seen anything like this! What do you think those trees are made of? They don't look like Earth trees at all!"

        I'm grinning despite everything—despite the pain in my leg, the dead pilots, the fact that I might die out here. I'm on an alien planet and Buddy is as excited as I am.

        Buddy adds —
        "The stream is eight hundred meters southwest. Want to explore on the way?"

        I say —
        "Absolutely."

        Southwest—right. I adjust my grip on the bag and start walking.

        And that's when the quiet hits me.

        ¶

        There is no birdsong, no insects buzzing, no rustle of small animals in the undergrowth—just wind moving through the canopy, a soft, almost musical sound deeper than Earth leaves, like the forest itself is breathing. My own footfalls become the loudest thing, muffled by the springy groundcover but still present.

        I ask Buddy —
        "Do you hear that? Or... not hear it?"

        Buddy says —
        "*It's so QUIET!* Where are the animals? Do you think there aren't any?"

        I say —
        "You said no fauna detected. So maybe... just plants?"

        Buddy says —
        "A whole planet with just plants? That's so weird! And cool! Is that possible?"

        I say —
        "It's happening, so... apparently?"

        Mav would love this—he'd probably do a whole episode about how the ecosystem works without pollinators or predators.

        The quiet is beautiful, in a way: peaceful but strange. Earth forests are never this silent—there's always something. Here there's only the soft breathing of thick leaves and my own footsteps.

        Buddy says quietly —
        "It feels like something's listening. Is that weird to say?"

        I answer —
        "No. I feel it too."
      </text>
