        The forest floor is oddly clear, too — no undergrowth tangling my feet, no fallen branches to navigate around. Just the purple-black groundcover and those massive trees, spaced far enough apart that walking between them is easy, almost like someone maintains it.

        That thought makes me uneasy, but I push it down and keep walking. The equipment bag digs into my shoulder. The air is thick — humid in a way that makes my skin feel damp, my hair already curling with moisture. It smells like growing things: sweet and earthy and floral all at once, with an edge of something unfamiliar underneath. Not bad. Just _other_. 

        The light shifts as I move deeper into the forest. Filtered through that purple canopy, everything takes on dreamlike lavender tones. Shadows aren't gray — they're purple-black, deep and soft. I pass a tree whose branches twist back toward the trunk in a way that makes my brain itch — wrong. The shapes are tree-like enough to be familiar but alien enough to remind me constantly: you're not home.

        Buddy notices — "The shadows are purple! Is that because the light is different?"

        I say, "Must be. The canopy filters out everything except the purple spectrum." I'm half-narrating in my head, describing this to an imaginary audience — "And here our intrepid explorer enters the purple forest..."

        Buddy asks, "Are you narrating? Like on Uncharted?"

        I laugh, caught. "Maybe. A little."

        Buddy brightens — "That's fun! Can I do it too?"

        I say, "Sure. What would you say?"

        Buddy tries, "And... Kira walks bravely through the alien forest, not knowing what awaits! The purple shadows hide many secrets!"

        I reply, "Pretty good! Very dramatic."

        Buddy: "Thanks! This is exciting!"

        It is. It really is. Despite everything

        ¶

        Pain flares up my leg, sudden and sharp enough to stop me mid-step.

        I've been walking on adrenaline, ignoring the bandaged wound, focused on getting to water. But the injury doesn't care about my focus. I lean against the nearest tree trunk — smooth bark, faintly warm even in the shade — and try to breathe through it.

        The bandage is seeping; I can see it darkening through my pants.

        Buddy's voice is worried — "Kira, your leg looks worse. Are you okay? Should we stop?"

        I say, "I'm fine. Just need a second."

        Buddy asks, "I don't want you to get hurt worse. How much farther to the water?"

        After a pause while Buddy calculates — "Approximately six hundred meters. Tell me if you need to stop, okay? Promise?"

        I answer, "I promise."

        Mav's voice in my head says, "The universe rewards the bold." But Mav had a medical team in orbit. I have Buddy and a bleeding leg and six hundred meters to go.

        I push off the tree and test weight on my leg. It hurts. It's going to keep hurting. But I can walk.

        So I do.

        The limp is more pronounced now. Adventure or not, I could die out here. Beauty doesn't make injury hurt less.

        I'm maybe fifty meters farther when I see it — movement high in the trees to my left, something shifting.

        I stop, heart suddenly pounding.

        I say, "Buddy, did you see that?"

        Buddy responds, "Something moved! I saw it too! What was it?"
      </text>
